## 2. MCP Responsibility Matrix

### 2.1 Authority levels
| Level | Scope                                    | May read | May mutate                                    |
|-------|------------------------------------------|----------|-----------------------------------------------|
| L0    | Read-only diagnostic                     | external runtime, external docs | nothing                                  |
| L1    | Reasoning support                        | only what's passed in           | nothing                                  |
| L2    | Backend / data mutation                  | project data layer              | project data layer (with migrations)     |
| L3    | Deployment / runtime mutation            | production runtime              | production runtime (deploy, env, rollback)|

No MCP currently in the active stack holds L4 (codebase mutation). Codebase mutation is **always** the main agent's responsibility through Read / StrReplace / Write.

### 2.2 Active MCP responsibility table

| MCP                  | Authority | Primary responsibility                          | Secondary responsibility                  | Forbidden domains                                         | Escalation condition                                              |
|----------------------|-----------|-------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Chrome DevTools      | L0        | Runtime browser inspection, performance profiling | Network analysis, console capture       | Aesthetic decisions, governance, code mutation, deployment | Any finding that conflicts with `performance-system.mdc` budgets |
| Context7             | L0        | Fetching current external library documentation | Verifying API surfaces vs training data  | Project codebase reasoning, cinematic decisions, governance | Documentation contradicts a `.rules/` constraint                 |
| Sequential Thinking  | L1        | Structured multi-step reasoning for complex governance decisions | Chapter density planning, atmospheric composition reasoning | Routine implementations, single-file edits, replacing creative direction | Reasoning chain exceeds 7 steps without convergence              |
| Supabase             | L2        | Backend data layer (audio credits, content metadata, contact storage) | Database schema migrations               | Cinematic / motion / atmosphere code, frontend rendering, deployment | Any schema change touching > 1 table or > 1 chapter's data       |
| Vercel               | L3        | Production deployment and monitoring            | Environment variable management, log retrieval | Source code, governance docs, migration execution, creative decisions | Failed deploy, performance regression in production, env-var change |

### 2.3 Per-MCP execution boundaries

#### Chrome DevTools (L0 — runtime analysis)
- ✅ May: open production / preview URLs; capture screenshots; record performance traces; inspect computed styles; capture console errors; measure paint / layout / scripting time.
- ❌ May NOT: propose visual changes; rewrite component code; recommend "premium" UX patterns; assert aesthetic improvements; modify any file.
- ⚠ Escalation: if Lighthouse Perf < 90, INP > 200ms, or any chapter exceeds its `performance-system.mdc §2` budget — escalate to main agent with the trace, do not attempt a fix.

#### Context7 (L0 — knowledge augmentation)
- ✅ May: fetch official docs for `next`, `react`, `gsap`, `lenis`, `three`, `@react-three/fiber`, `@react-three/drei`, `framer-motion`, `tailwindcss`, `@gsap/react`, `split-type`, `tunnel-rat`.
- ❌ May NOT: fetch documentation about the project's own codebase (use Read / Grep / Glob instead); fetch competitor / inspiration sites to "match"; fetch tutorials about "premium" web design; fetch AI-aesthetic references.
- ⚠ Escalation: when fetched docs contradict any `.rules/` constraint or any HC-XX canon correction, **do not act on the docs** — log the contradiction, surface it, ask the operator.

#### Sequential Thinking (L1 — reasoning support)
- ✅ May: be invoked for chapter density composition, cross-chapter atmospheric continuity reasoning, performance trade-off analysis, debugging multi-system failures, architecting new motion patterns within the existing vocabulary.
- ❌ May NOT: replace creative direction; resolve open questions in `MASTER_STATE.md §7` autonomously; reason about decisions already governed by `DESIGN_DNA.md`, `cinematic-language.mdc`, or any locked rule.
- ⚠ Escalation: if reasoning produces a chain of > 7 thoughts without converging on a decision, halt the chain and escalate to main agent / operator.

#### Supabase (L2 — backend data)
- ✅ May: read project schema; create / alter tables for narrative backend systems (e.g., contact form storage, audio credits index, content metadata); apply versioned migrations; manage RLS policies for shipped backend features.
- ❌ May NOT: store cinematic / motion / atmosphere configuration (those live in code as tokens); modify frontend code; alter governance docs; provision databases without migration commits in the repo.
- ⚠ Escalation: any schema change touching > 1 table, any RLS policy change, any change to a table consumed by a chapter — requires PR review with `infra:` prefix and operator sign-off before applying to production.

#### Vercel (L3 — deployment / runtime)
- ✅ May: trigger deployments from confirmed branches; read deployment logs; inspect environment variables; perform manual rollback; monitor production performance.
- ❌ May NOT: change source code; modify `.rules/` or `/docs/`; promote experimental branches; bypass CI gates (`DEVELOPMENT_GUIDELINES.md §14.2`); change environment variables without operator sign-off.
- ⚠ Escalation: any deploy failure; any production performance regression triggering an alert; any environment variable change.

