│                       OPERATOR                                │
│              (creative direction authority)                   │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                              │ task
                              ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                     MAIN AGENT                                │
│   reads continuity layer · writes source code · owns session  │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                              │
       ┌──────────────────────┼──────────────────────┐
       ▼                      ▼                      ▼
┌─────────────┐      ┌─────────────────┐      ┌──────────────┐
│ SUBAGENTS   │      │ MCPs (L0 / L1)  │      │ MCPs (L2/L3) │
│ explore     │      │ Chrome DevTools │      │ Supabase     │
│ browser-use │      │ Context7        │      │ Vercel       │
│ shell       │      │ Seq. Thinking   │      │              │
└─────────────┘      └─────────────────┘      └──────────────┘
   (read-only          (read / reason          (mutate w/
    artifacts)          only)                   safeguards)
```

### 3.4 Escalation rules
An invocation **must escalate to the main agent** (and may escalate further to the operator) when:
- An MCP returns a result that conflicts with any `.rules/` constraint.
- An MCP-suggested action would touch the continuity layer.
- A subagent reports a blocker outside its delegated slice.
- Two or more MCP findings appear to contradict each other.
- An L2 / L3 MCP would mutate state in production.
- A reasoning chain via Sequential Thinking exceeds 7 steps without convergence.

Escalation is **synchronous** — the chain halts until the main agent resolves. There is no "best effort continue" mode.

### 3.5 Review chain
For any MCP-driven action that produces a code change, doc change, or runtime change:

```
MCP output → main agent verification → human reviewer → CI gates → merge
```

No step is skipped. An MCP suggestion that bypasses any of these is a **process violation**.

### 3.6 Ownership precedence
When two actors could own a task, this is the precedence:

```
Operator > Main agent > L0 MCP > L1 MCP > L2 MCP > L3 MCP > Subagent
```

Higher-precedence actors may delegate to lower; lower-precedence actors **never** initiate without higher authority.

