## 7. Performance Governance

### 7.1 Orchestration overhead limits
- ≤ **5 MCP invocations per session** under normal operation.
- ≤ **3 Sequential Thinking chains per session**, each ≤ **7 steps**.
- ≤ **2 Chrome DevTools traces per session** unless actively debugging a regression.
- ≤ **1 Context7 fetch per library per session** (cache the answer in agent reasoning, do not re-fetch).
- ≤ **1 Supabase migration per session** (per §6.2).
- ≤ **1 Vercel deploy per branch in flight at a time** (per §6.2).

If a session exceeds these limits, the orchestration is **over-spent**. Pause and re-evaluate scope.

### 7.2 Context efficiency
- An MCP call must **earn its context cost**. The main agent estimates the input + output token cost of an MCP invocation and skips it if the same answer can be obtained via a < 1k token Read / Grep call.
- Context7 fetches are summarized in agent reasoning, not pasted verbatim. The full fetch is **not** preserved across turns.
- Chrome DevTools traces are filtered to the relevant timeline window before inclusion in reasoning. Full traces are not pasted.

### 7.3 MCP invocation discipline
- Pre-invocation: state in one sentence why this MCP, why now, what the expected output enables.
- Post-invocation: state what was learned and what the next step is.
- A pre/post block is **not optional**. It is the audit trail.

### 7.4 Reasoning budgets
- A complex architectural decision (e.g., wiring a new chapter) may use Sequential Thinking once, ≤ 7 steps.
- A routine implementation (e.g., new scene matching an existing pattern) **may not** use Sequential Thinking — it indicates the agent did not consult the relevant `.rules/` and `/docs/` first.
- A Context7 fetch is reasonable when implementing against an unfamiliar library API. It is **not** reasonable for routine GSAP / Lenis / Three patterns already documented in the project.

### 7.5 Tool-call minimization
- The single best metric for orchestration health is **fewer tool calls per session**, not more.
- An "AI looks busy" tool call (running a check no one asked for) is forbidden.
- Tool calls that produce information the agent already had **before the call** are process failures and should be flagged in self-review.

### 7.6 Forbidden orchestration economics
- ❌ Unnecessary orchestration — calling an MCP because it exists, not because the task requires it.
- ❌ Tool spam — multiple MCP calls to "be thorough" when one would suffice.
- ❌ Recursive execution chains — MCP A's output triggers MCP B which triggers MCP A.
- ❌ Excessive context hydration — loading more than 30k tokens of project context across the session.

